<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>Semantic HTML Example</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      margin: 0;
    }
    header, footer {
      background-color: #333;
      color: white;
      padding: 1em;
    }
    nav a {
      margin: 0 1em;
      color: white;
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    section {
      padding: 1em;
    }
    article {
      margin-bottom: 2em;
      padding: 1em;
      background-color: #f0f0f0;
      border-left: 4px solid #007acc;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <header>
    <h1>This is the Header Section</h1>
    <p>The header typically contains the title of the page and main navigation.</p>
    <nav>
      <a href="#">Home</a>
      <a href="#">About</a>
      <a href="#">Contact</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>This is a Section Element</h2>
    <p>The section groups related content together, such as blog posts or news items.</p>

    <article>
      <h3>This is the First Article</h3>
      <p>This article represents a self-contained piece of content, like a blog post or news entry. Articles should make sense on their own and often have their own heading.</p>
    </article>

    <article>
      <h3>This is the Second Article</h3>
      <p>Here is another article, showing how multiple articles can live within a section. Each article can focus on a different topic while still being related.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <footer>
    <p>This is the Footer Section â€” typically used for copyright notices, contact info, or links to policies.</p>
    <p>&copy; 2025 Semantic HTML Example. All rights reserved.</p>
  </footer>

</body>
</html>
